bioghist.head: Biographical / Historical
bioghist.p: The Sheffield Scientific School, like the Graduate School, had its origins in the Department of Philosophy and the Arts established in 1847. It was given its name by the Yale Corporation in 1861 in recognition of the support of Joseph Earl Sheffield of New Haven who not only gave the first building but also provided funds for its equipment and development. Subsequently he made other gifts and finally bequeathed to a corporation, the Board of Trustees of the Sheffield S cientific School, a substantial endowment which was to be held and adninistered by the Trustees for the benefit of the natural, physical, and mathematical sciences in Yale University.

Sheffield was one of the first schools of higher education in the United States to devote its curriculum specifically to scientific training. The School played an important part in the evolution of American higher learning from the strict classical model of education t o a curriculum which encompassed a liberal scientific education.

The faculty of the School conducted graduate as well as undergraduate courses i n the sciences and engineering until 1919 when the former were discontinued. In 1932, engineering instruction was transferred to the newly organized Yale School of Engineering. In 1945 Sheffield resumed its original function of teaching at the graduate level. Under the general administration of the Graduate School, its faculty furnished instruction to graduate students in the sciences and mathematics who were M.A. and Ph.D. candidates. In 1956 the School's functions were absorbed by the Graduate School. The Directors of Sheffield Scientific School were: George Jarvis Brush, 1872-1898; Russell Henry Chittenden, 1898-1922; Charles Hyde Warren, 1922-1945; Edmund Ware Linnott, 1945-1956.
For further information see History of the Sheffield Scientific School of Yale University, 1846-1922 by Russell H. Chittenden (New Haven: Yale University Press, 1928).

professorship of Civil Engineering established the Yale School of Engineering is organized under William A. Norton

Engineering courses are offered in the Scientific School

eventgrp.event: degree of Doctor of Philosophy from the Scientific School established

the Sheffield Scientific School, through an Act of the Connecticut General Assembly, begins to receive the income from the Land Grant Fund of the State

Russell Henry Chittenden, Director of the Sheffield Scientific School

eventgrp.event: graduate courses are transferred to the Graduate School

general reorganization of the educational structure of Yale University. Three year "Select" course at the Shef f ield Scientific School eliminated. A four year course of study "for students who wished to undertake the professional study of science and engineering" established

chronitem.event: only undergraduate courses taught at the Sheffield Scientific School
first award of the degree of Bachelor of Science to the graduating class of the Sheffield Scientific School
the School of Engineering re-established. Sheffield Scientific School engineering courses transferred to the new school

the Sheffield Scientific School resumes its original function of graduate level instruction in science. Undergraduate courses for a Bachelor of Science transferred t o Yale College. Undergraduate courses for a Bachelor of Science in industrial administration transferred to the School of Engineering
Edmund Ware Sinnott, Director (also Dean of the Graduate School, 1950-1956)
Centennial celebration of the Sheffield Scientific School

termination of the Sheffield Scientific School as an active school although the Board of Trustees still exists to oversee the Sheffield Scientific School property and meet legal requirements. Yale University Provost becomes Chairman of the Board. Faculty is defined as teachers of science to graduate students under the Division of Science

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: The records consist of correspondence, minutes, reports, financial records, student records and papers, photographs and memorabilia, grade books, clippings, class records, memoranda, notes, a copy of the 1944 charter and by-laws of the Board of Trustees of the Sheffield Scientific School and administrative files documenting the history and operations of the Sheffield Scientific School and relate to virtually every aspect of its activities.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The records are arranged in eleven series and subsequesnt accessions: I. Trustees and Governing Board Records, 1871-1967. II. Faculty Minutes, circa 1852-1945. III. Administrative Records, 1864-1956. IV. Financial, Legal, and Property Records, 1846-1969. V. Silliman Lectures. VI. Student Life, 1901-1949. VII. Student Papers, 1877-1909. VIII. Engineers Club, 1895-1918. IX. Class Records, 1869-1969. X. Photographs and Memorabilia, circa 1848-1951. XI. Class Registers, Lists, and Grade Books, 1848-1951.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series I contains the records of the Sheffield Scientific School's policy setting and administrative bodies - the Board of Trustees, responsible for overseeing property and finances, and the Governing Board, responsible for curriculum development, faculty appointments and other academic matters.

The Trustees Records 1871-1967 is comprised of minutes of the Executlve Committee meetings and the Board of Trustees meetings, financial papers, including Treasurer's reports, Auditor's reports, funds and bequest materlal and correspondence.

The Governing Board Records 1872-1956 consists of a complete set of minutes. Included in these volumes are recommendations for faculty appointments and promotions, committee reports, curriculum approval and recommendations of candidates for degrees.

The materials in Series I are grouped into sections by administrative unit: the Board of Trustees, the Executive Committee and the Governing Board. The materials within each section are arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series II, FACULTY MINUTES, 1860-1945, documents the Sheffield Scientific School's day-to-day academic and student related activities. The minutes contain, among other things, information on curriculum, catalogue descriptions, teaching schedules, examination results, minutes of the class instructors meetings, action taken with students'in academic trouble and student discipline.

The Sheffield Scientific School faculty was originally called the Board of Instructors. Beginning on October 24, 1932, the Sheffield Scientific School faculty met jointly with the School of Engineering faculty. It should be noted that these minutes are not complete to 1956 and that gaps exist in the time span represented.
The materials in Series II are arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.p: Series III, ADMINISTRATIVE RECORDS, is divided into ten sections:

list.item: Charles Hyde Warren and Edmund W. Sinnott, 1922-1956
Committee on the Selection of a Successor to Sheffield Scientific School Director Russell H. Chittenden, 1921-1922

scopecontent.p: Materials include correspondence, policy statements, Yale University reorganization material, early admissions material, personnel records, several histories of the Sheffield Scientific School, and information regarding the effects of the two world wars on the Sheffield Scientific School. There is no material from the George Jarvis Brush administration (1872-1898).

The Sheffield Scientific School served as the land grant agricultural college for Connecticut from 1863-1893. The primary function of the Appointing Board and the State Board of Visitors was to fill vacancies in state scholarships to the Sheffield Scientific School. The minutes of the Appointing Board meetings record routine business and procedures as well as choice of scholars and awarded funds. Official Notices consists of forms and notices issued from the Directors and/or Registrar's Offices from 1860s- 1940s. Materials include announcements, exam schedules, meal forms, notices of school closings, and commencement activities.

Director Russell H. chittendents correspondence is arranged alphabetically by correspondent or subject of the correspondence. Note: for a list of Russell Henry Chittenden selected correspondents see Appendix I. These papers contain one major subsection - World War I Activities - organized alphabetically by subject. The papers of Directors Charles Hyde Warren and Edmund W. Sinnott are combined in one file arranged alphabetically by correspondent or subject. These papers contain one major subgroup - Personnel Records - arranged alphabetically by person or department.

The Annual Reports are arranged chronologically. Committee on the Sefection of a Successor to Sheffield Scientific School Director Russell H. Chittenden, Appointing Board Records and Semi-Centennial Celebration Records are organized by form. Centennial Celebration Records are organized alphabetically with one major subsection - the Committee on Arrangements. The Student Register and Official Notices are arranged chronologically.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series IV, FINANCIAL, LEGAL, AND PROPERTY RECORDS, is divided into eight sections:
Materials within each of these sections are arranged alphabetically and/or chronologically.

Historical Papers contains materials relating to the Sheffield Scientific School's early development: correspondence, the Articles of Incorporation of the Board of Trustees and bequest information among others. Because of their size and nature the historical papers were arbitrarily pulled together into a combined chronological and alphabetical subsection. Legal Matters re: Trustee Property contains deeds for land and buildings and agreements for building use by others. Building Construction and Maintenance contains contracts and related papers for construction, renovation and upkeep of the buildings. Legal Documents re: Funds contains materials relating to donations of land and money. Materials in the George St. John Sheffield Bequest section include the will, inventories, correspondence and financial and tax matters. The Amelia Daggett Sheffield Estate section contains materials regarding the estate settlement and distribution: the will., inventories, appraisals and release forms. The George Sheffield Fund material includes correspondence, financial papers and reports summarizing fund supported research from 1938-1952.
Financial Records and Reports is divided into six subsections:
These provide a fairly complete picture of the Sheffield Scientific School's financial development and status.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Endowed in 1901, the Silliman Memorial Lectureship funded an annual series of lectures "the general tendency of which may be such as will illustrate the presence and wisdom of God as manifested in the Natural and Moral World." After presentation, the guest expanded his material into book form to be published by the Sheffield Scientific School. Series V, SILLIMAN LECTURES 1906, 1911-1956, contains the administrative data compiled by the Silliman Lecture Committee, Materials include correspondence suggesting lecturers, invitations, acceptances, declinations, Corporation votes affirming lecturers, correspondence discussing lecture topics and material re : publication of the manuscripts. See Appendix 2 for a list of Silliman Lecturers.

The materials in Series V are arranged in three sections: Lecturers, Invited Lecturers Who Did Not Accept or Were Unable to Attend, and Suggested Lecturers. The materials within each section are arranged chronologically according to the academic year the Silliman Lecture was given.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series VI, STUDENT LIFE, is organized into three sections:

Material in the Fraternities section includes correspondence, prize information and discussion of discipline problems, The Student Council Records contains constitutions, correspondence, social business, honor code examinations and discipline. In 1932-1933, the Student Council began to serve both the Sheffield Scientific School and the newly created School of Engineering. The Young Men's Christian Association Records consists of the minutes of the Executive Committee and general membership meetings and financial business.
The materials within the Fraternities and Student Council sections are arranged alphabetically. The materials within the Young Men's Christian Association section are organized by form.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series VII, STUDENT PAPERS 1877-1911, contains unpublished these submitted by students applying for a Bachelor of Philosophy or an advanced degree. Most of the papers date from 1895 to 1905. The papers deal with scientific or engineering topics; most include plates, diagrams and reproductions.
The papers are organized alphabetically by author.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Contents
scopecontent.p: Series IX, CLASS RECORDS 1869-1969, contains correspondence and memorabilia from sixteen classes between 1869.-and 1908. The records of the Class of 1901 are most complete and are representative of the types of material found in other years. These include Class Secretary and/or Class Agent correspondence, financial records, biographical data and statistics on graduates, reunion material, photographs, slides and memorabilia.
Arranged chronologically according to class year. Materials within each section are organized alphabetically.
